	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Background: Kenyan civil society actors warn of the risks of EPAs</h1>

			
			<h4>
												14 September 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> Major concerns about the impact of the EU-ESA EPA negotiations were expressed by Kenyan civil society actors in a statement on February 4 th 2004 . Their first concern was that the introduction of a simple free-trade area agreement was 'incompatible with the development needs of ACP countries’. The increased market access that the EU is seeking for its goods and services 'will pose serious threats to already vulnerable local food production, local food processing and infant manufacturing industries in ACP countries’.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> The Kenyan Civil Society also expressed concern over the imbalance in political and economic power within the negotiations, a factor exacerbated by aid dependency on the EU.</p><p> The statement also expressed concern over the impact of EPA negotiations on regional integration processes and the failure to conclude a binding agreement at the end of the all-ACP phase of the negotiations. It called for the establishment of 'a rigorous set of benchmarks and principles’ to guide the negotiations.</p><p> Consideration of the negotiating guidelines for the eastern and southern African configuration raised the need for a modification of WTO rules 'on regional trading agreements between developed and developing countries to allow for preferential trade arrangements which are consistent with the level of development of the respective parties and which fully accommodates the diverse development needs of ACP countries’. More specifically the statement called for longer time-frames for the transition to reciprocity and a more limited product coverage than that envisaged by the EC (90%).</p><p> A number of other recommendations were made in the report, including calls for:</p>
<ul>

<li>the incorporation of special and differential treatment into all aspects of the EPA negotiations and for concrete initiatives to be taken to address supply-side constraints; </li>

<li>'safeguards to deal with disruptive surges of imports’ and for a simplification of the rules of origin; </li>

<li>ESA governments to demand 'an immediate elimination of all export subsidies and a substantial reduction of domestic support as part of the EPA negotiations’, given that 'the EU is a major distorter of the world agricultural trade’; </li>

<li>ESA governments to 'insist that the impact of CAP reform on ACP economies must be comprehensively addressed as an integral part of the EPA negotiations’ because 'the shift from price support to direct aid to farmers might have an impact both on the income ACP countries earn from agricultural exports to the EU and the competitive threat posed to local food production’; </li>

<li>detailed analysis of the impact of CAP reform so that 'relevant negotiating objectives can then be developed including, for example, compensatory mechanisms for the losses that ACP countries would suffer.’ </li>

</ul>
<p> The statement also included sections expressing concerns on the ' Singapore issues’ and trade in services.</p><p> Overall the statement concluded that 'economic partnership agreements as envisaged by the EU will be detrimental to the developing and least developed ACP countries’. It called for deferment of any liberalisation under EPAs until 'issues such as improvement of the WTO rules, implementation of measures to address supply-side constraints, the conclusion of regional market integration processes in the ACP countries, elimination of EU’s export subsidies and trade-distorting agricultural support, are ensured’. It also called for the completion of the all-ACP phase of the negotiations and the conduct of detailed impact-assessment studies on the effects of EPAs on the eastern and southern African region.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			

<ul>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.epawatch.net/general/text.php?itemID=161&amp;menuID=28" target="_self">Kenyan Civil Society statement on the launching of the EU-ESA EPA negoti...</a> </li>

</ul>
		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> In many respects the statement of the Kenyan Civil Society actors reflects underlying ACP concerns arising from the unresolved issues from phase I of the EPA negotiations, most notably with regard to:</p>
<ul>

<li>ensuring that EPAs are not just free-trade areas but tools for structural development; </li>

<li>the adequacy of WTO rules on free-trade areas where groupings of least developed and developing countries are negotiating with developed economies; </li>

<li>the importance of safeguards in the context of the changing pattern of CAP distortions; </li>

<li>the need for sustainability impact assessments that feed directly into the negotiating process. </li>

</ul>

		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

